{"title_page": "Padborg", "text_new": "'''Padborg''' ({{lang-de|Pattburg}}) is a southern [[Denmark|Danish]] [[border town]] with a population of 4,361 (1 January 2019)<ref>[https://m.statbank.dk/TableInfo/BY3?lang=en BY3: Population 1st January, by urban areas] The Mobile Statbank from [[Statistics Denmark]]</ref> located on the border with [[Germany]]. Padborg is the southernmost locality in Denmark. It is the location where both the [[European route E45|E45]] [[motorway]], a [[railway]] and the historic Danish Army Road, ''[[h\u00e6rvejen]]'', cross the border. Located a few kilometres northwest of [[Schleswig]]'s historic commercial centre, [[Flensburg]], Padborg was a small settlement when the [[South Jutland County|region]] returned to Danish rule in 1920 following a [[Schleswig Plebiscites|plebiscite]], but grew rapidly in size after the establishment of the current border. It is a transport centre and [[railway town]]. When the border was established in 1920, the originally planned border line was moved c. 200 metres south of Padborg in order to allow construction of the [[Padborg station|railway station]] and a customs office.\nPadborg is well known in Denmark for its motorsport ring, [[Padborg Park]], and the head offices of the large discount chain Fleggaard.\n\nPadborg has a broad based transport industry with most of the largest European transport companies having local offices.\nPadborg is located in [[Aabenraa municipality]]. Until 31 December 2006 it belonged to [[Bov municipality]].\n\n== Notable people ==\n* [[Niels-Peter M\u00f8rck]] (born 1990 in Padborg) a Danish football midfielder who plays for Italian club Virtus Bolzano\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n{{Coord|54|49|22|N|9|21|21|E|region:DK_type:city|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Cities and towns in the Region of Southern Denmark]]\n[[Category:Denmark\u2013Germany border crossings]]\n[[Category:Aabenraa Municipality]]\n{{Denmark-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Padborg''' ({{lang-de|Pattburg}}) is a southern [[Denmark|Danish]] [[border town]] with a population of 4,361 (1 January 2019)<ref>[https://m.statbank.dk/TableInfo/BY3?lang=en BY3: Population 1st January, by urban areas] The Mobile Statbank from [[Statistics Denmark]]</ref> located on the border with [[Germany]]. Padborg is the southernmost locality in Denmark. It is the location where both the [[European route E45|E45]] [[motorway]], a [[railway]] and the historic Danish Army Road, ''[[h\u00e6rvejen]]'', cross the border. Located a few kilometres northwest of [[Schleswig]]'s historic commercial centre, [[Flensburg]], Padborg was a small settlement when the [[South Jutland County|region]] returned to Danish rule in 1920 following a [[Schleswig Plebiscites|plebiscite]], but grew rapidly in size after the establishment of the current border. It is a transport centre and [[railway town]]. When the border was established in 1920, the originally planned border line was moved c. 200 metres south of Padborg in order to allow construction of the [[Padborg station|railway station]] and a customs office.\nPadborg is well known in Denmark for its motorsport ring, [[Padborg Park]], and the head offices of the large discount chain Fleggaard.\n\nPadborg has a broad based transport industry with most of the largest European transport companies having local offices.\nPadborg is located in [[Aabenraa municipality]]. Until 31 December 2006 it belonged to [[Bov municipality]].\n\n== Notable people ==\n* [[Niels-Peter M\u00f8rck]] (born 1990 in Padborg) a Danish football midfielder who plays for Italian club Virtus Bolzano\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n{{Coord|54|49|22|N|9|21|21|E|region:DK_type:city|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Cities and towns in the Region of Southern Denmark]]\n[[Category:Denmark\u2013Germany border crossings]]\n\n{{Denmark-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "ArbieP", "label": "safe", "comment": "addedCategory:Aabenraa Municipality", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Padborg"}
